In Python, input().split() splits the input into parts, then map to integers. So in C, using scanf("%d %d", &A, &B) should work to read two integers. Then compute ans = A - 2 * B. Then check if ans is less than zero. If yes, set ans to zero. Then print it. So in C, the code structure would be:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int A, B, ans;
    scanf("%d %d", &A, &B);
    ans = A - 2 * B; if (ans < 0) {
        ans = 0;
    }
    printf("%d\n", ans);
    return 0;
} Wait, that seems straightforward. Do I need to handle any edge cases? Like if the input has more numbers, but the problem probably assumes correct input.

